{
  "answer": "**Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Chapter 1**\n\nIn its section on witnesses (1.5), the *Bṛhaspati Smṛti* enumerates twelve kinds: a subscribed witness, a recorded witness, **a concealed witness**, a reminded witness, a kinsman, a messenger, a chance witness, a secondary witness, one present at the transaction, a king, a chief judge, and the village.[^1]\n\n**The concealed witness (*gūḍhaḥ sakṣī*)** is defined as follows:\n\n> He who, concealed by a wall, is made to hear a statement about a debt, and who, when it is denied, relates it as it happened, is called a concealed witness.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-0cc2ab).\n\n[^2]: Bṛhaspati Smṛti, Chapter 1, [paragraph](/works/unknown-brhaspati-smrti-0fd070/01/translation/#p-2ee353).",
